<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,272,498]" box="[151,289,272,297]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis box="[151,289,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,272,498]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Specimens small, 
<quantity box="[410,536,312,338]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.9" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.8" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="49.0" valueMax="60.0" valueMin="38.0">38–60 mm</quantity>
long, largest 
<quantity box="[700,783,312,338]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="14.0">14 mm</quantity>
wide, vermiform. Colour, in alcohol, uniform pinkishbeige, slightly darker dorsally, speckled with white, indicating accumulation of spicules. Podia small, scattered, better developed ventrally. Mouth anterior, collar absent; anus terminal, surrounded by special anal papillae in five radial clusters. Stone canal short, slightly twisted; madreporite spherical; Polian vesicle single. Cuvierian tubules absent.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077025" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5077025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077025/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" startId="18.[151,255,1915,1939]" targetBox="[203,1385,593,1882]" targetPageId="18">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1435,1915,1973]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,283,1915,1939]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">FIGURE 7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Selenka, 1867" authorityName="Selenka" authorityYear="1867" box="[293,855,1915,1938]" class="Holothuroidea" family="Holothuriidae" genus="Holothuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aspidochirotida" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="pardalis" subGenus="Lessonothuria">
<emphasis box="[293,689,1915,1938]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Holothuria (Lessonothuria) pardalis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Selenka, E." box="[698,855,1915,1938]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="109 - 118" refId="ref30967" refString="Selenka, E. (1867) Nachtrag zu den Beitragen zur Anatomie und Systematik der Holothurien. Zeitschrifte fur wissenschaftliche, Zoologie, 18, 109 - 118." type="journal article" year="1867">Selenka, 1867</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Inhaca. A. pseudobuttons from body wall; B. tables with spinose discs; C. podial rods; D. end-plate; E. tentacle rods. (All drawn to same scale)
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,152,458]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Table discs of body wall (
<figureCitation box="[483,603,152,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,593,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-126@18.[168,1419,557,1889]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 7. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) pardalis Selenka, 1867. Inhaca. A. pseudobuttons from body wall; B. tables with spinose discs; C. podial rods; D. end-plate; E. tentacle rods. (All drawn to same scale)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077025/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figure 7B</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[619,739,152,178]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.9" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="4.8" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="59.0" valueMax="70.0" valueMin="48.0">48–70 µm</quantity>
(mean 
<quantity box="[825,905,152,178]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="56.0">56 µm</quantity>
), with distinctly spinose rim with four central and usually a single series of smaller marginal holes, the latter often reduced, then discs incomplete; spire extremely low, 
<quantity box="[331,451,232,258]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.45" metricValueMax="4.8" metricValueMin="4.1" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="44.5" valueMax="48.0" valueMin="41.0">41–48 µm</quantity>
(mean 
<quantity box="[538,616,232,258]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="45.0">45 µm</quantity>
), terminating in few teeth. Pseudobuttons (
<figureCitation box="[1123,1245,232,258]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,593,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-126@18.[168,1419,557,1889]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 7. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) pardalis Selenka, 1867. Inhaca. A. pseudobuttons from body wall; B. tables with spinose discs; C. podial rods; D. end-plate; E. tentacle rods. (All drawn to same scale)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077025/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figure 7A</figureCitation>
) of diverse size, 
<quantity box="[151,272,272,298]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.55" metricValueMax="6.8" metricValueMin="4.3" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="55.5" valueMax="68.0" valueMin="43.0">43–68 µm</quantity>
(mean 
<quantity box="[361,441,272,298]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="56.0">56 µm</quantity>
), and shape, either complete with 3–5 pairs of holes, or incomplete with asymmetrically placed holes, rarely reduced to a single series on one side. Podial deposits include usually elongate, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.39" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="0.48" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="139.0" valueMax="230.0" valueMin="48.0">48– 230 µm</quantity>
(mean 
<quantity box="[332,427,352,378]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.39" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="139.0">139 µm</quantity>
), curved rods (
<figureCitation box="[603,724,352,378]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,593,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-126@18.[168,1419,557,1889]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 7. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) pardalis Selenka, 1867. Inhaca. A. pseudobuttons from body wall; B. tables with spinose discs; C. podial rods; D. end-plate; E. tentacle rods. (All drawn to same scale)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077025/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figure 7C</figureCitation>
) with one or two perforations at each end, rarely reduced to short rods with more perforations; end-plates (
<figureCitation box="[730,858,392,418]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,593,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-126@18.[168,1419,557,1889]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 7. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) pardalis Selenka, 1867. Inhaca. A. pseudobuttons from body wall; B. tables with spinose discs; C. podial rods; D. end-plate; E. tentacle rods. (All drawn to same scale)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077025/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figure 7D</figureCitation>
) (ca. 
<quantity box="[937,1035,392,418]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="250.0">250 µm</quantity>
) present. Tentacles with simple, slightly curved, non-perforate rods, 
<quantity box="[572,693,432,458]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="3.1" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="48.0" valueMax="65.0" valueMin="31.0">31–65 µm</quantity>
(mean 
<quantity box="[780,860,432,458]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.3" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="43.0">43 µm</quantity>
), with uneven margins (
<figureCitation box="[1141,1263,432,458]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="18.[151,255,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,593,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-126@18.[168,1419,557,1889]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 7. Holothuria (Lessonothuria) pardalis Selenka, 1867. Inhaca. A. pseudobuttons from body wall; B. tables with spinose discs; C. podial rods; D. end-plate; E. tentacle rods. (All drawn to same scale)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077025/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figure 7E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,701,512,578]" box="[151,701,512,578]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis box="[151,294,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Distribution</emphasis>
Tropical-subtropical Indo-Pacific, 0–? 
